          "text": "Deliberate choice, not convenience. The candidate to reuse was `ChatMessageResponse` (the full message DTO), and I rejected it on four grounds:\n\n1. **Payload scaling.** `parts` is the complete message content — an assistant reply with reasoning and tool payloads can be tens of KB. The list endpoint returns every owned chat, so embedding the full DTO makes `GET /chats` scale with *total conversation content* instead of *number of chats*. The feature is a preview; shipping the whole message to render 160 chars defeats it.\n\n2. **The excerpt is server-owned derivation, not data.** Text-parts-only, whitespace-collapsed, truncated — if the API returned the raw message, every client re-implements that (web today; Telegram/Discord channel clients later, per the roadmap). One server-side implementation keeps previews identical everywhere and lets the truncation limit change without touching clients.\n\n3. **Egress discipline.** The repo convention (SPEC §22.0 / the `toPublicUser` allowlist pattern) is explicit response types with deliberately chosen fields. A preview has three consumers-with-a-purpose: `role` (styling/\"You:\" prefixes), `excerpt`, `createdAt`. Reusing the full DTO would ship `senderUserId`, `usage`, `inReplyTo`, `attachments`, `seq` into a list surface with no consumer — wider contract for nothing.\n\n4. **Contract decoupling.** If the message shape evolves (parts format, usage fields), the list contract stays stable; a `lastMessage: ChatMessageResponse` would ripple every message change into the list schema.\n\nThe steelman for reuse: zero new types, and clients could derive any preview they want. That's the right call when clients are trusted to need arbitrary slices — but here it costs payload, duplicated derivation, and egress width to save one small, named, OpenAPI-documented DTO. \"Ad-hoc\" would be an anonymous inline object; `ChatLastMessageResponse` is a purpose-built projection, which is what the code-first-OpenAPI convention in `apps/api` calls for.\n\nThe web-side `ChatLastMessage` type in `queries.ts` follows from that: it mirrors the REST contract, and there was no existing web type for it — `UIMessage` is the AI SDK's streaming shape, not this endpoint's.\n\nWhere it bends: if the list ever needs more of the message (attachment indicators, say), the projection gets extended field-by-field. That's the intended maintenance mode — each addition is a visible contract decision rather than an accidental inheritance.",
