ext/cache/**` negation.** Every repo's `build` task outputs `[\".next/**\", \"!.next/cache/**\", \"dist/**\"]` or a per-app variant of it. Undeclared outputs = no caching, per Turborepo docs.\n\n**Pattern seen in 3/4 — `dependsOn: [\"^build\"]` for the standard build-order graph.** Universal for anything that consumes a workspace package's build output (types, transpiled code). cal.com/midday add non-cached utility tasks (`db-*`, `post-install`, `dev`) with `\"cache\": false` explicitly.\n\n**Split, not consensus — legacy `pipeline` key vs. Turborepo 2.x `tasks` key.** cal.com and midday have migrated to `\"tasks\"` (turbo 2.x); **documenso and dub are still on the old `\"pipeline\"` key** despite referencing `turbo.build/schema.json`. This is a real-world signal that \"everyone's on turbo 2.x conventions\" is false — worth noting since llame should just use `tasks` (current schema) without worrying about matching an imagined universal convention.\n\n**`globalDependencies`/`globalEnv` hygiene — inconsistent, and cal.com is a cautionary tale.** cal.com's `globalEnv` is a ~250-entry flat list of every env var in the whole app — this busts caching granularity (any env var change invalidates every task's hash) and is explicitly what Turborepo's own docs warn against (prefer per-task `env` over `globalEnv` for exactly this reason — \"a lint task probably doesn't need to miss cache when an API key changes\"). documenso does the same (large flat `globalEnv`). midday is the outlier and the better model: minimal `globalDependencies` (`**/.env`) and pushes provider secrets into `passThroughEnv` on the `build` task specifically, not `globalEnv` — this scopes env-based cache-busting to the tasks that actually need those secrets. **Recommendation: use `env` on specific tasks, reserve `globalEnv` for truly cross-cutting vars (NODE_ENV, CI), and never let it become a dumping ground.**\n\n**Per-package `turbo.json` (Package Configurations) is real but rare in the wild** — only midday uses it (`packages/mcp-apps/turbo.json` with `extends: [\"//\"]`), consistent with official guidance to reach for it \"when multiple packages need different task configurations\" rather than `package#task` overrides cluttering root config. For llame's current 2-app, 2-package footprint, root-level `package#task` overrides (cal.com's style) are simpler and sufficient — package-level `turbo.json` is a scaling response, not a day-1 requirement.\n\n**Naming inconsistency confirmed across all sources — no canonical typecheck task name.** cal.com: `type-check:ci`; midday: `typecheck`; official with-nestjs example: `check-types`; Turborepo's own docs examples use `check-types`. Pick one and don't worry about matching an external \"standard\" — there isn't one.\n\n### 2. CI cache persistence\n\n**This is the most consequential finding: half of the comparable repos don't persist a turbo cache in CI at all.**\n\n- **cal.com**: uses Vercel Remote Cache exclusively (`TURBO_TOKEN`/`TURBO_TEAM` as secrets in `check-types.yml`, `api-v2-unit-tests.yml`, `unit-tests.yml`) — no `actions/cache` on `.turbo/`. It layers this with a custom composite action caching the *git checkout itself* (`actions/cache` keyed on commit SHA to skip re-clone) and a very elaborate yarn install cache (download cache + node_modules cache + install-state cache, each independently restorable) via `.github/actions/yarn-install`.\n- **documenso**: sets `TURBO_TOKEN`/`TURBO_TEAM` **only in `e2e-tests.yml`**, not in the main `ci.yml` build job — so their primary build/lint path gets zero turbo cache benefit; only e2e reuses it.\n- **dub**: **no turbo remote cache anywhere.** Its only caches are `actions/cache` for Playwright browsers and `setup-node`'s built-in pnpm store cache. This is a well-funded, actively maintained project shipping without any `.turbo` persistence — evidence that remote caching is a speed optimization, not table-stakes for correctness.\n- **midday**: uses Vercel Remote Cache but **reuses existing deployment secrets** — maps `TURBO_TOKEN: secrets.VERCEL_TOKEN` and `TURBO_TEAM: secrets.VERCEL_ORG_ID` instead of minting dedicated Turbo secrets. Since they already deploy through Vercel, this avoids secret sprawl. It also runs `turbo build --affected --dry-run=json` in a `detect-changes` job to gate which app-specific deploy/test jobs run at all (matrix-style fan-out per affected app), and every subsequent job uses `turbo lint/typecheck/test --affected`.\n\nNone of the 4 use `rharkor/caching-for-turbo` or the GitHub-Actions-native cache backend — **Vercel-hosted remote cache (or none) is what's actually deployed in this class of repo**, despite `rharkor/caching-for-turbo` being the community-recommended non-Vercel option per 2025 articles (successor to the now-broken `dtinth/setup-github-actions-caching-for-turbo`).\n\n**Article-sourced points not contradicted by any repo (safe to adopt directly):**\n- `TURBO_TEAM` should be a repo **variable**, not a secret — GitHub censors secret values in logs, which breaks readable output; `TURBO_TOKEN` should be the secret. (Official Turborepo docs, matches documenso's `vars********TEAM` usage.)\n- Affected-only execution (`--filter`/`--affected` with `fetch-depth: 0`) is a bigger CI-time lever than caching alone — confirmed practice in midday, called out in the WarpBuild article as \"the biggest lever.\"\n- Run related tasks through one `turbo` invocation (`turbo build lint test`) rather than separate sequential steps, to let Turborepo's own scheduler parallelize — none of the 4 repos actually do this (they all run `lint`, `check-types`, `test` as separate CI jobs/steps), so treat this as an article recommendation with no empirical confirmation from the sampled repos, not a strong pattern.\n\n**Recommendation for llame specifically** (CI without turbo cache persistence today): adding Vercel Remote Cache costs one secret + one variable and is the path with the most precedent (cal.com, midday) and official first-class support — it's a five-minute add, not an infra project. If avoiding a Vercel account dependency matters, `rharkor/caching-for-turbo` is the documented non-Vercel path, though no comparable repo in this sample actually runs it in production, so treat it as unproven-by-example rather than battle-tested.\n\n### 3. Workspace layout conventions\n\n**Package naming**: all 4 repos scope packages to `@&lt;org&gt;/*` (`@calcom/*`, `@documenso/*`, `@midday/*`; dub's package.json names weren't scoped the same way but its apps/packages still sit under `packages/*`). The official `with-nestjs` example and Turborepo's best-practices doc use the generic `@repo/*` placeholder scope. llame's `@workspace/ui` already matches this convention.\n\n**Shared TS config package naming — `tsconfig` beats `typescript-config`/`config-typescript` 3-to-1 among the real repos** (cal.com, documenso, dub, midday all name it `packages/tsconfig`), while the *official* Vercel example uses `packages/typescript-config`. llame's `packages/config-typescript` is a third variant nobody in the sample uses verbatim — not wrong, but worth knowing it's an outlier naming choice if consistency-with-ecosystem is a goal (it isn't a functional issue).\n\n**Root `tsconfig.json` isn't needed** — official guidance: \"each package should have its own config extending from the shared config package,\" root config is optional/thin. Confirmed structurally in the with-nestjs example (root tsconfig just extends `@repo/typescript-config/base.json` with one override).\n\n**e2e location has no dominant convention — 3 different answers across 3 repos.** cal.com and dub colocate Playwright under `apps/web/playwright/`; documenso uses a **dedicated package** `packages/app-tests/e2e/`. llame's repo-root `e2e/` is a fourth, equally legitimate pattern (matches Playwright's own scaffolding default) — there's no \"correct\" convention to converge on here.\n\n**Package manager choice is genuinely split**: cal.com=yarn (berry/v4), documenso=npm, dub=pnpm, midday=bun. pnpm is not the universal default this ecosystem's reputation suggests — it's one of four live choices among comparable, well-run projects. Not a reason to reconsider llame's pnpm choice, just a caveat against over-indexing on \"pnpm is the standard.\"\n\n**Emerging pattern worth flagging**: midday uses **dependency-catalog syntax** (`\"@ai-sdk/openai\": \"catalog:\"`, resolved via a root `\"catalog\"` key, bun's equivalent of pnpm's `catalog:` feature) to centralize shared dependency versions across packages instead of repeating version strings per package.json. If llame accumulates more packages sharing pinned deps (AI SDK, Zod, etc.), pnpm's native `catalog:` support (pnpm-workspace.yaml `catalog:`) is worth adopting before version drift becomes a problem — not urgent at 2 packages.\n\n### 4. Anti-patterns to avoid\n\n1. **A sprawling flat `globalEnv` list** (cal.com's ~250 entries, documenso similarly large) — defeats fine-grained cache hashing; Turborepo's own docs warn against exactly this. Use per-task `env`/`passThroughEnv` instead (midday's model).\n2. **Turning on remote cache in some CI jobs but not others** (documenso: only in e2e, not the main build) — inconsistent, easy to do by accident, leaves the bulk of CI time uncached.\n3. **Staying on the legacy `pipeline` key** in `turbo.json` (documenso, dub) when Turborepo 2.x's `tasks` key has been current for well over a year — no functional harm today, but it's config debt that will eventually force a migration; start on `tasks` now (llame likely already is, but worth confirming as this repo's config gets built out).\n4. **Assuming \"everyone runs tasks through one combined `turbo` invocation for parallelism\"** — the article advice sounds authoritative but none of the 4 real repos actually do it; don't restructure CI around an unconfirmed claim.\n5. **Treating turbo remote cache as mandatory** — dub ships without any `.turbo` persistence in CI. It's worth adding for llame