          "text": "Nothing is *wrong* with it — it's deferred on one verified concern and one unknown. To be precise, this is **Turbopack's** filesystem cache for *production builds* (`experimental.turbopackFileSystemCacheForBuild`), not Turborepo's cache (which we did wire up in #121). The dev-side equivalent is already stable, on by default since 16.1, and we benefit from it today.\n\nWhy I didn't enable the build-side flag:\n\n1. **Still experimental on our version** (16.2.10). It reached GA-as-opt-in recently and is exactly the kind of flag that gets renamed/promoted between minors — 16.3's release notes already touch it. Cheap to wait for the 16.3 upgrade.\n2. **The real unknown: Sentry.** Our build wraps `withSentryConfig`, which runs a debug-ID injection pass over the emitted chunks and uploads sourcemaps (`widenClientFileUpload`). There's no documentation confirming that a build replayed from Turbopack's persistent cache produces debug IDs consistent with what gets uploaded — if cached chunks carry stale IDs, production stack traces silently stop symbolicating. That's a \"works fine until you need an error report\" failure mode, so I wasn't going to turn it on unproven. To be clear: no known-bad report exists either — it's genuinely unverified, not broken.\n3. **It's not free to enable** — it interacts with our Turborepo outputs. We deliberately exclude `.next/cache/**` from turbo's cached outputs; with the flag on, that exclusion throws away exactly the directory the feature reads from, so enabling it means flipping the outputs glob (and rechecking CI cache size).\n\nThe payoff if it clears: Vercel benchmarks 2.3–5.5× faster warm production builds.\n\n**Plan when you want it:** after bumping to 16.3 — enable the flag on a branch, build twice, verify the second build's injected debug IDs match Sentry's uploaded artifacts (and that an error event symbolicates), then include the Turbopack cache subdir in `apps/web/turbo.json` outputs and measure. If the Sentry