)\n- **`workspace:` protocol** forces local linking instead of registry resolution; rewritten to a real version/`npm:` spec on publish. Pairs with `linkWorkspacePackages` — set to `false` if you want workspace linking to require the explicit `workspace:` protocol rather than happening implicitly by name match.\n- **Filtering (`--filter`)** — richer than most teams use: glob (`--filter \"./packages/**\"`), `[&lt;since&gt;]` for changed-since-a-ref (`pnpm --filter \"...[origin/master]\" test`, prefix/suffix `...` pulls in dependents/dependencies), and combinations like `--filter \"{packages/**}[origin/master]...\"`. Useful even alongside Turborepo's own affected-package detection for scripts Turbo doesn't orchestrate. [pnpm.io/filtering](https://pnpm.io/filtering)\n- **`pnpm deploy`** — builds a portable, isolated production artifact for one workspace package (`pnpm --filter=&lt;pkg&gt; --prod deploy &lt;dir&gt;`); dependencies (incl. workspace ones) get installed into a self-contained `node_modules` at the target. Since v10, deploy **requires `inject-workspace-packages: true`** by default (or `--legacy`/`force-legacy-deploy`) — a documented friction point for teams that don't want injected deps just for deploy. [pnpm.io/cli/deploy](https://pnpm.io/cli/deploy), [discussion #9015](https://github.com/orgs/pnpm/discussions/9015)\n- **Patching** (`pnpm patch &lt;pkg&gt;` → edit → `pnpm patch-commit`): persists as a `patches` entry + patch file for dependency fixes without forking. [pnpm.io/cli/patch](https://pnpm.io/cli/patch)\n- **Overrides**: root-only field, can target a scoped dependency-of-dependency (`\"qar@1&gt;zoo\": \"2\"`), remove a subdep with `-`, and reference a catalog entry to keep override and normal version in lockstep.\n- **Injected dependencies** (`injectWorkspacePackages`): copies (rather than symlinks) a workspace dependency's build output into consumers, needed when a package must see its dependency's compiled output rather than source — not needed for you today since `packages/ui` is source-consumed.\n- **Side-effects cache** (`sideEffectsCache`/`sideEffectsCacheReadonly`): caches build-script side effects (native addon build output) keyed by inputs, so packages with `install`/`postinstall` scripts don't rebuild on every install with a warm store.\n\n### 2. Performance\n\n- Core model unchanged: **content-addressable store** + hard links into a per-project virtual store (`node_modules/.pnpm`), giving pnpm's headline disk/speed advantage over npm/Yarn classic hoisting.\n- **`enableGlobalVirtualStore`** (v10.12.1+): symlinks `node_modules` from one shared central virtual store keyed by dependency-graph hash across *all* projects on the machine (conceptually like Nix). Speeds up warm installs significantly, but pnpm auto-disables it in CI (no warm cache there) — so it's a local-dev-only win, not a CI one. In v11 this is now default-on for `pnpm add -g`/`pnpm dlx`.\n- **v11: SQLite-backed store index** replaces the old JSON-per-package index file — faster store lookups at scale.\n- **`frozenStore`** (v11.7.0): lets `pnpm install` run against a read-only store (Nix store, read-only bind mount, OCI layer) — opens `index.db` immutable, skips all store-write paths. Relevant if you ever want Nix-store-backed CI installs given your Nix-managed dev environment.\n- **CI caching**: confirmed best practice unchanged — cache `pnpm store path`, not `node_modules` (caching node_modules risks broken symlinks and defeats hard-linking from the store anyway). `actions/setup-node@v4` with `cache: 'pnpm'` (what you're already doing) is still the recommended path; `pnpm/action-setup@v6` also gained native `cache: true` if you want more control. [pnpm.io/continuous-integration](https://pnpm.io/continuous-integration)\n- v11 also **fails on lockfiles written by a newer major** in CI instead of silently rewriting — keep CI's pnpm version ≥ the one that generated your lockfile.\n\n### 3. v10.x/v11 items worth adopting regardless of the bun question\n\n- **`allowBuilds`** (added v10.26.0) — successor to `onlyBuiltDependencies`/`neverBuiltDependencies`/`ignoredBuiltDependencies`; a single map (`allowBuilds: { esbuild: true, core-js: false }`), can pin allow/deny per exact version. In **v11 the old settings are removed entirely** and `allowBuilds` + `strictDepBuilds` (default `true`, errors on unreviewed builds) is the only mechanism. A codemod exists: `pnpx codemod run pnpm-v10-to-v11`. Since you're on 10.4.1 with `onlyBuiltDependencies: [esbuild]`, this still works today but is a dead-end setting — worth switching to `allowBuilds` now so a future v11 bump is a no-op.\n- **Git dependency `prepare` scripts now blocked by default** (semi-breaking, ~10.26) unless explicitly allowed — closes a supply-chain gap if you ever pull git-hosted deps.\n- **Env-var expansion restricted** (10.34.2+/11.5.3+, GHSA********x77r): pnpm no longer expands `${ENV_VAR}` in repo-controlled `.npmrc`/`pnpm-workspace.yaml` registry/credential settings — closes a secret-exfiltration vector via a malicious cloned repo. Directly relevant given your BYOK/secrets posture.\n- Multiple **lockfile path-traversal hardenings** landed through the year (config-dependency names/versions, hoisted-mode alias validation) — reinforces that staying current on the 10.x line (not just pinning early) is itself a security-relevant practice, independent of any v11 move.\n- **Tarball integrity backfill**: pnpm now computes and persists integrity hashes for registries that can't supply them, closing a lockfile-verification gap.\n- v11 adds `pnpm ci`, `pnpm sbom` (`--exclude-peers`), `pnpm clean`, `pnpm peers check`, `pnpm runtime set`, plus `pn`/`pnx` short aliases — not urgent but useful once you move majors.\n\n### 4. Known pain points at scale\n\n- **Strict peer resolution vs. npm/Yarn-shaped hoisting expectations** is the recurring NestJS/monorepo complaint: pnpm's isolated `node_modules` means a transitive dep two packages disagree on version-wise gets installed twice rather than silently hoisted/deduped — surfaces as \"Nest can't resolve dependencies of X\" or type mismatches between two copies of the same package (documented against `@nestjs/schedule`→`cron`). [nestjs/nest#13463](https://github.com/nestjs/nest/issues/13463), [pnpm discussion #9691](https://github.com/orgs/pnpm/discussions/9691)\n- Maintainer-endorsed fixes, in order of preference: (1) convert the tightly-coupled transitive dep into an explicit `peerDependency` upstream, or a local `pnpmfile.cjs` `readPackage` hook to declare it as a peer; (2) `peerDependencyRules.allowedVersions` to accept the mismatch explicitly; (3) scoped `publicHoistPattern` for a specific offending package. **Never** reach for global `shamefully-hoist` as a permanent fix — you trade away the phantom-dependency guarantees that are pnpm's whole point.\n- CI/local nondeterminism: local dev usually has `auto-install-peers: true` silently papering over gaps; CI's `--frozen-lockfile` enforces strictness and fails where the laptop didn't. Run `pnpm install --strict-peer-dependencies` locally periodically to catch this before CI does.\n- `nodeLinker: hoisted` remains the escape hatch for tooling that can't handle symlinks (React Native being the classic case) — not something Next 16/Nest 11 should need, but worth knowing it exists if a third-party tool in your stack chokes on the isolated layout.\n\n### Features you're not using that would pay off\n\n1. **Catalogs** — highest-leverage adopt. With React 19 needed by both `apps/web` and `packages/ui`, and TypeScript/config versions shared across all 4 workspaces, a `catalog:` block in `pnpm-workspace.yaml` collapses version drift risk to one edit point and removes a class of merge conflicts on `package.json` bumps. Low effort, no behavior change beyond version pinning discipline.\n2. **`allowBuilds` over `onlyBuiltDependencies`** — free forward-compat move now, avoids a forced edit if/when you bump to v11.\n3. **Bump pnpm itse