docs](https://docs.sentry.io/platforms/javascript/guides/bun/). Its `BunServer` integration instruments `Bun.serve` — irrelevant to us since apps/api runs Express, not `Bun.serve`; we'd fall back to generic Node-compat instrumentation, which is even less validated. |\n| **AI SDK v5/v6 SSE streaming on Bun+Express 5** | Works-with-caveats (thin evidence) | No direct GitHub bug reports found for AI SDK-on-Bun breakage. Vercel's own Bun Runtime beta explicitly lists Express as supported with \"response streaming\" as a feature ([Vercel Bun runtime blog](https://vercel.com/blog/bun-runtime-on-vercel-functions)) — the strongest positive signal. Weak negative signal: a community dev had to hand-roll the AI SDK data-stream protocol under Bun+Express because a testing helper \"failed to work with ai/test directly\" (dev-tooling gap, not core streaming breakage). Overall: plausible but unverified for this exact combination in real production traffic. |\n| **Real Next+Nest(-like) monorepos on Bun in production** | None found | Multiple Next+NestJS Turborepo examples exist, but all use npm/yarn/pnpm, none Bun. **midday-ai/midday** — the closest \"TypeScript SaaS fully on Bun\" public precedent — deliberately chose **Hono**, not NestJS, for its API layer. This absence is itself signal: nobody has publicly de-risked \"Nest on Bun in prod\" at scale. |\n\n### Bottom line\n\n**Minimal viable adoption (recommend this, if any):** Bun as **package manager only**, root + all workspaces — install/scripts, keep Node as the actual runtime everywhere (dev, build, `next start`, `nest start`, tests, CI, Docker prod images). This is fully de-risked: Turborepo 2.6+ has stable (non-beta) Bun PM support with correct `bun.lock` v1 parsing, Vercel's `bun install` is zero-config and long-standing, and none of the runtime-level bugs above (Turbopack/Bun, Nest CLI, decorator-metadata regressions, Playwright IPC hangs, drizzle JSON bug) are triggered by using Bun purely as an installer. Net win is faster `pnpm install`→`bun install` in CI/dev; near-zero new risk. Would still need to verify oxlint/prettier/lefthook function identically when invoked via Bun's script runner (no compatibility concerns found — they're either Rust binaries or plain Node scripts).\n\n**Maximal adoption (not advisable now):** Running Bun as the actual runtime across the stack (`bun --bun next dev/build/start`, Nest under `bun run`, pg-boss worker on Bun, Playwright via `bun test`, Sentry via `@sentry/bun`) stacks multiple simultaneously-open, unresolved upstream issues that each individually hit a component this stack depends on: Turbopack Fast-Refresh storms and a hard runtime warning against `cacheComponents` (Next 16's flagship feature), a live JSON-column bug in drizzle-orm+Bun, no official Nest CLI support, Playwright's own team calling multi-worker Bun stability an open blocker, and Sentry's Bun SDK still beta with no Express-adjacent instrumentation path validated. None of these are individually fatal, but collectively there's no public evidence anyone has run this specific combination (Nest+Express 5+Bun, Next 16 Cache Components+Turbopack+Bun, Playwright e2e+Bun) in production. Full-runtime Bun migration should wait for: Next.js Turbopack/Bun issues to close, Nest CLI to gain first-party Bun support, and Playwright's multi-worker Bun mode to leave \"known blocker\" status.\n\nSources cited inline above (GitHub issues, official docs/blogs from Vercel, Bun, Sentry, NestJS, Playwright, Drizzle, node-postgres teams).</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>193037</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>23</tool_uses><duration_ms>217230</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>",
