          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>af76********61ba</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********sQNs</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-llame--claude-worktrees-redesigned-sidebar/a96f1f63-a7f3-48f4-84d8-3004f53f80c9/tasks/af76c0cfbff4a61ba.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Bun docs and maturity research\" finished</summary>\n<note>A task-notification fires each time this agent stops with no live background children of its own. The user can send it another message and resume it, so the same task-id may notify more than once.</note>\n<result># Bun mid-2026 brief — package manager, runtime, test runner\n\n**Context note:** Anthropic acquired Bun/Oven on Dec 2, 2025 (confirmed via anthropic.com press release) — Claude Code ships as a `bun build --compile` executable, which was Anthropic's stated motive. Post-acquisition, a RedMonk analysis reports significant contributor turnover and heavier AI-authored commits; treat Bun's roadmap/governance as in flux relative to pre-acquisition norms. [Anthropic announcement](https://www.anthropic.com/news/anthropic-acquires-bun-as-claude-code-reaches-usd1b-milestone), [RedMonk analysis](https://redmonk.com/sogrady/2026/06/04/bun-two-lessons/)\n\n---\n\n## 1. Bun as monorepo package manager — Verdict: **capable, still shaking out edge cases**\n\n- **Workspaces**: standard `\"workspaces\"` field, full glob support incl. negative patterns (`!**/excluded/**`). [Bun workspaces docs](https://bun.com/docs/pm/workspaces)\n- **Catalogs** (explicitly pnpm-inspired): shipped for testing in **1.2.14**, GA in **1.3** (Nov 2025). Root `package.json` `\"catalog\": {...}` block, workspace packages reference via `\"catalog:\"`. `bun outdated` and `bun update -i` support catalog deps. [Bun 1.3 blog](https://bun.com/blog/bun-v1.3)\n- **Lockfile**: `bun.lock`, text-based JSONC, introduced **1.2** (Jan 2026) replacing the old binary lockfile — addressed a long-standing complaint about diffability/PR review/merge conflicts.\n- **Isolated installs**: introduced in **1.3**, made **default for workspaces** in 1.3.0. Each package only sees its declared deps (vs. npm/Yarn-style flat hoisting) — explicitly framed as fixing \"the #1 issue users faced with Bun in large monorepos\" (phantom deps). Opt-out via `bun install --linker=hoisted` or `bunfig.toml` `[install] linker = \"hoisted\"`.\n  - **This was rocky at launch.** [GitHub issue #23615](https://github.com/oven-sh/bun/issues/23615) documented isolated-installs + catalogs being effectively broken for production monorepos at 1.3.0 (catalog dedup failures, stale cache on version bump). Bun's team responded fast: **1.3.1** fixed cross-volume `EXDEV` errors on macOS + added `publicHoistPattern`/`hoistPattern` selective hoisting; **1.3.2** introduced a lockfile `configVersion` system so pre-existing projects (no lockfile version) keep the old hoisted default and only new projects get isolated-by-default — a real back-compat break they had to patch around; **1.3.13** fixed hanging installs in peer-heavy monorepos; **1.3.14** added an experimental global store for isolated installs.\n  - **Read**: isolated installs are the right direction (matches pnpm's model) but the 1.3.0 launch was under-tested against real monorepos, and it took ~4 point releases to stabilize.\n- **Patch/overrides**: `overrides` supported in `package.json` (npm-style). 1.3 bugfixes include `--frozen-lockfile` + overrides interaction and lockfile parsing with workspace overrides — i.e., this codepath was buggy enough to need multiple fixes, a signal it's not deeply battle-tested yet. No first-class `bun patch` equivalent to pnpm's `patch`/`patch-commit` surfaced in my research — didn't find one; treat as a gap vs. pnpm.\n- **`pnpm deploy` equivalent**: **not found**. `bun pm pack` (tarball) exists, but there's no dedicated \"deploy this workspace package + its resolved deps into an isolated target dir\" command analogous to `pnpm deploy`. This is a real gap for Docker-multistage / trimmed-deployment workflows in a monorepo.\n- **Security scanner API** (new in 1.3): pluggable scanner interface, launch partner is Socket (`@socketsecurity/bun-security-scanner`), configured via `bunfig.toml [install.security]`. Scans on `install`/`add`, can block on `fatal` advisories.\n- **Performance claims vs. independent benchmarks**: Bun's own/vendor claims: 30% faster than 1.1 (1.2), and vendor-style 2026 comparisons converge on **Bun ~2-5x faster than pnpm 10 on cold installs**, larger multiples vs. npm (up to 17x on small projects). Mechanism: Zig-native binary, ~165k syscalls vs npm's 1M+. **But pnpm wins on disk efficiency** — content-addressable store + hard links gives ~75-87% disk savings across projects with overlapping deps; Bun's isolated linker gets only ~5% savings by comparison in one benchmark. **Compatibility risk quoted at ~95%** Node compat, meaning real risk of package-level surprises, and **native addons (node-gyp) don't work under Bun at all**.\n- **Turborepo + \"Bun as PM only, Node as runtime\"**: well-supported and reasonably common pattern. Turborepo docs show `devEngines.packageManager` config for Bun; real-world configs use `\"packageManager\": \"bun@1.3.4\"` at root while services run via `node dist/index.js`. Renovate has friction updating the `packageManager` field for Bun-managed repos. This pattern (Bun installs, Node executes) is explicitly a hedge people take to get install speed without runtime-compat risk — worth considering for this repo if you ever want faster CI installs without touching `apps/api`'s Node runtime.\n\n## 2. Bun as runtime — Verdict: **production-viable for HTTP/web workloads, real gaps in worker/async-instrumentation depth**\n\nCompat matrix pulled directly from [bun.com/docs/runtime/nodejs-compat](https://bun.com/docs/runtime/nodejs-compat) (documented against Node.js v23 baseline):\n\n| Module | Status | Detail |\n|---|---|---|\n| `node:http` | 🟢 Fully implemented | Caveat: outgoing client request body is **buffered, not streamed** |\n| `node:https` | 🟢 | APIs implemented, but `Agent` \"not always used\" |\n| `node:http2` | 🟡 | Client &amp; server implemented, 95.25% of gRPC's test suite passes; missing `allowHTTP1`, `enableConnectProtocol`, ALTSVC, `pushStream` |\n| `node:stream` | 🟢 Fully implemented | |\n| `node:net` | 🟢 Fully implemented | |\n| `node:tls` | 🟡 | Missing `tls.createSecurePair` |\n| `node:worker_threads` | 🟡 | `Worker` doesn't support `stdin`/`stdout`/`stderr`/`trackedUnmanagedFds`/`resourceLimits` options; missing `markAsUntransferable`, `moveMessagePortToContext` |\n| `node:async_hooks` | 🟡 | `AsyncLocalStorage` and `AsyncResource` implemented; **v8 promise hooks not called**, and Bun's own docs say usage is \"strongly discouraged\" |\n| `node:crypto` | 🟡 | Missing `secureHeapUsed`, `setEngine`, `setFips`; but 1.3 shipped major perf wins (DiffieHellman ~400x, cipher/decipher ~400x, scrypt ~6x faster vs 1.2) |\n| `node:cluster` | 🟡 | FD/handle passing between workers not supported except Linux `SO_REUSEPORT`; otherwise \"implemented but not battle-tested\" |\n| `node:child_process` | 🟡 | Missing `proc.gid`/`proc.uid`; IPC can't pass socket handles |\n| `node:perf_hooks` | 🟡 | APIs present but Node's own test suite for the module doesn't pass |\n| Node-API (napi) | Core surface complete (156/156 functions) per tracking issue #158 | Remaining gaps are behavioral parity: async_hooks lifecycle events not emitted from napi async calls, libuv loop semantics differ (Bun doesn't run on libuv on Linux/macOS) |\n\n**Open GitHub issue themes** (oven-sh/bun): worker_threads stability tracking (#15964) — finalizer/buffer-callback ordering on `Worker.terminate()` doesn't match Node; several crash reports (segfaults, panics) trace through `worker_threads`/`async_hooks` code paths in watch mode, CI builds, and concurrent-connection scenarios — pattern suggests worker/threading edge cases are the more fragile corner of the runtime, not core HTTP.\n\n**V8 (Node) vs JSC (Bun)**: JSC optimizes for fast startup/low memory (Bun: ~8-15ms cold start vs Node ~40-120ms); V8's multi-tier JIT (Sparkplug/Maglev/TurboFan) wins on sustained throughput for long-running warmed-up processes. Synthetic HTTP benchmarks favor Bun 3-4x; once DB/routing/I-O dominate, the gap narrows to single-digit percent in most sourced comparisons — i.e. the runtime choice matters far less than people's synthetic benchmarks suggest for typical CRUD/API workloads (relevant to `apps/api`'s NestJS Postgres-bound request path). One serverless (Lambda) case study: Bun 290ms cold start / 14.1k req/s vs Node 940ms / 9.8k req/s.\n\n**Production track record**: adoption is now credible (Anthropic/Claude Code CLI itself ships as a Bun-compiled binary; Midjourney, Lovable cited as adopters), but sourced caveats consistently flag long-running (72h+) processes as less proven than Node's GC, and anything depending on native (node-gyp) addons as a hard blocker. Node still holds the vast majority of production/enterprise share.\n\n## 3. Dev/debug story — Verdict: **functional but visibly behind Node's inspector ecosystem**\n\n- `bun --inspect` / `--inspect-brk` / `--inspect-wait` speak the **WebKit Inspector Protocol** (not Chrome DevTools Protocol) — ws server, works with Bun's own hosted web debugger at `debug.bun.sh` (a modified Safari-style Web Inspector UI).\n- **VS Code**: official `bun-vscode` extension (published by Oven) is explicitly labeled **experimental**. Attach-mode (`ws://localhost:6499/`) is more reliable than launch-mode for complex dev servers (Vite/Nuxt) — community-documented workaround is `stopOnEntry: true` + `--inspect-wait` because launch-mode routinely misses initial source-map generation and breakpoints silently don't bind.\n- Source maps: work automatically for uncaught-exception stack traces (including from TS, no config needed) — this part is genuinely good. But interactive breakpoint debugging through source maps in complex bundler/dev-server setups is the rough edge described above.\n- **Compared honestly to Node**: Node's inspector speaks CDP directly, so it plugs into Chrome DevTools and the mature VS Code Node debugger with no protocol-translation layer and no \"experimental\" label. Bun's debugging story works for simple scripts/services; for anything behind a dev-server/bundler layer, expect friction Node users don't have.\n\n## 4. Tooling\n\n- **`bun test`**: Jest-API-compatible for the *common* subset (describe/it/expect, mocking, coverage flags, watch mode, custom error messages via `expect()` added in 1.2). **1.3 added `node:test` support**, running actual Node test-suite tests through `bun:test` under the hood.\n  - **Breaks on**: workspace/monorepo mocking, Prisma mocking, MSW, complex `jest.mock` hoisting, custom transformers/serializers, `jest-environment-jsdom`-dependent suites. Coverage (`bun --coverage`) is explicitly still experimental, no HTML reports/branch coverage maturity. Watch mode is coarse (re-runs everything, no Vitest-style dependency-graph HMR). Only runs inside Bun, not portable to Node-based CI without installing Bun.\n  - Realistic framing: fine for greenfield, mostly-server-side TS test suites; risky to blindly migrate an established Jest monorepo suite onto it. For this repo (Playwright e2e + presumably Jest/Vitest-style unit tests in `apps/api`), a wholesale switch to `bun test` would need validation against Drizzle/Postgres test fixtures and any mocking-heavy suites first.\n- **`bun build`**: matured meaningfully in 1.3 — programmatic `Bun.build({compile:true})` API (standalone executables without the CLI), cross-platform/cross-arch compiles (`--target=bun-linux-x64` etc. from any host), code signing for Windows/macOS, full-stack (frontend+backend) single-file executables, native HMR dev server (React Fast Refresh via `import.meta.hot`). 1.3.14 fixed a real perf bug (~8KB struct copied by value per AST node) for ~12% faster module loading; also fixed a use-after-free crash in the dev server triggered by atomic-rename editors (vim/emacs/IntelliJ) — i.e., the bundler/dev-server is still finding real memory-safety bugs at this stage, not just feature gaps.\n- **`bun run`**: mature as a script runner; not much controversy found either way.\n- **Bun-as-PM-only-with-Node-runtime**: supported and documented as a real pattern (see §1), not exotic.\n\n## 5. Release trajectory summary\n\n- **1.2** (Jan 22, 2026(sic — actually Jan 2026 per search, i.e. this year)): text `bun.lock`, S3 object storage support, HTML imports, `node:http2`/`node:cluster`/`node:dgram` improvements, `node:zlib` rewritten to native code, 30% faster installs, \"90%+ of Node's test suite passes for supported modules\" framing introduced; catalogs shipped experimentally in point release 1.2.14.\n- **1.3** (~Nov 2025): isolated installs default for workspaces, catalogs GA, Security Scanner API, `node:test` support, VM module support, worker `environmentData` API, crypto perf (~400x on some primitives), bundler overhaul (compile API, cross-platform builds, full-stack single-file executables), `Bun.stripANSI()`. Point releases 1.3.1–1.3.14 spent heavily on **stabilizing isolated installs/catalogs** (this was the dominant bug theme) plus bundler/dev-server crash fixes.\n- **Open pain-point themes** (from GitHub issues, cross-cutting): worker_threads/async_hooks behavioral parity (not missing, but subtly wrong under load or on terminate), isolated-installs edge cases in unusual monorepo topologies, native-addon incompatibility, debugging DX behind bundler layers.\n\n---\n\n### Bottom line for this repo's decision-making\n- **As PM**: Bun catalogs + isolated installs are now roughly at pnpm-catalog feature parity on paper, but the 1.3.0 launch bugs (#23615) and the config-versioning back-compat patch in 1.3.2 indicate this is a **6-month-old feature**, not proven infrastructure — pnpm 10 remains the safer default for this